<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="sec_relationsfunctions">
  <title> Relations and Functions </title>

  <subsection> 
    <title>
      Relations
    </title>
    <definition>
      <title>Relations</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A mathematical <term>relation, <m>\mathrel{R}</m>, between two sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m></term> is a collection of ordered pairs from the two sets. Expressed symbolically, <m>\mathrel{R} \subseteq A \times B</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We call set <m>A</m> the <term>domain</term> and the set <m>B</m> the <term>codomain</term>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>a</m> is related to <m>b</m> we will write <m>a \mathrel{R} b</m> or <m>(a,b) \in \mathrel{R}</m>. If two elements <m>c </m> and <m>d</m> are not related, we write <m>c \cancel{\mathrel{R}} d</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex_sib">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If we consider <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> to both be the set of people in your family, and let <m>\mathrel{R}</m> be the relation <q><m>a</m> is a sibling of <m>b</m>.</q> Here's an example of my family in two graphical representations. What are the ordered pairs that make up the relation? 
        </p>
        <p>
        <sidebyside widths="30% 30%" valign="middle">
          <image xml:id="graph-sib">
            <description>Standard Cartesian graph showing my siblings. The horizontal and vertical axes are family members, labeled John, Eric, and Sarah. There is a dot on the graph when the two are related, so dots at (John, Eric), (John, Sarah), (Eric, John), (Eric, Sarah), (Sarah, John), and (Sarah, Eric). </description>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
              \draw[thin, gray!50] (0,0) grid (4, 4);
              \draw[thick] (0,4) node[left] {} -- (0,0) -- (4,0) node[below right] {};
              \draw (1,0) node[below] { John} (0, 1) node[left] { John};
              \draw (2,0) node[below] { Eric} (0, 2) node[left] { Eric};
              \draw (3,0) node[below] { Sarah} (0, 3) node[left] { Sarah};
              \fill (1,3) circle (.1) (1,2) circle (0.1) (2,3) circle (.1) (2,1) circle (.1) (3,2) circle (.1) (3,1) circle (.1);
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <image xml:id="my-family-graph">
            <description>Graph of two sets A and B. Elements on the left are John, Eric, and Sarah; elements on the right are John, Eric and Sarah. There is a line from John to Eric and John to Sarah; a line from Eric to John and Eric to Sarah; and a line from Sarah to John and Sarah to Eric.</description>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}
              \coordinate (A)  at (0,3);
              \node at (A) [below]{};
              \coordinate (B)  at (0,2);
              \node at (B) [left]{John};
              \coordinate (C)  at (0,1);
              \node at (C) [left]{Eric};
              \coordinate (D)  at (0,0);
              \node at (D) [left]{Sarah};

              \coordinate (E)  at (2,3);
              \coordinate (F)  at (2,2);
              \coordinate (G)  at (2,1);
              \coordinate (H)  at (2,0);

              \node at (E) [below]{};
              \node at (F) [right]{John};
              \node at (G) [right]{Eric};
              \node at (H) [right]{Sarah};
              \draw (B) -- (G) -- (D) -- (F) -- (C) -- (H) -- (B);
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          </sidebyside>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Looking that the points on the graph, we see that the relation will be the set of ordered pairs:
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{Siblings} = \{(\text{John}, \text{Eric}), (\text{John}, \text{Sarah }),
            (\text{Eric}, \text{John}), (\text{Eric}, \text{Sarah}),
            (\text{Sarah}, \text{Eric}),(\text{Sarah}, \text{John})\}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Notice that these ordered pairs correspond to the lines on the graph diagram with each of the first coordinates being connected to the second coordinate. E.g. an arrow goes from John to Eric.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex_divides_relation">
      <title>The Divides Relation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> both be the set of integers from 1 to 10, and define the relation by <m>a \mathrel{R} b</m> means that <m>a</m> evenly divides into <m>b</m> with no remainder.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here are some examples of the divides relation:
          <ul>
            <li>
              <m>2 \mathrel{R} 4</m> since 2 divides into 4 evenly.  There is no remainder.
            </li>
            <li>
              Similarly, <m>5 \mathrel{R} 5</m> since it divides into itself. No remainder.
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>4 \cancel{\mathrel{R}} 3</m> since 4 doesn't divide into 3. The remainder is 1.
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>6 \cancel{\mathrel{R}} 3</m> since 6 doesn't divide into 3. The remainder is 3.
            </li>
          </ul>
          Now, complete the following questions:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <!-- Draw a graphical representation of the divides relation as we did in the sibling example, listing elements of the two sets and drawing lines from the left set to the right where the line means <m>a</m> divides evenly into <m>b</m>. -->
              Complete the following graph of the relation below, where a point on <m>(x,y)</m> means that <m>x </m> divides evenly into <m>y</m>. 
              <image xml:id="graph-relation-blank" width="50%">
